            <div type="translation">
                <p>… κριτοῦ τοῦ βήλου καὶ ἐπὶ τοῦ κανικλείου τοῦ Λιβελλησίου.</p>
                <p xml:lang="en">(Seal of) N. Libellesios, krites of the Velum, and epi tou
                    kanikleiou.</p>
                <p xml:lang="de">(Siegel des) N. Libellesios, krites des Velum und epi tou
                    kanikleiou.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" subtype="text">
                <p xml:lang="en">It is likely that the first name of the issuer was inscribed on the
                    obverse. While it has not survived, it can be reconstructed as Ioannes thanks to
                    another seal type whose reverse is parallel to ours. It is unfortunate that the
                    inscription on the obverse of the seal has not survived, as it could have
                    provided important information concerning the motives behind Ioannes
                    Libellesios' selection of matrices. </p>
            </div>
            <div type="bibliography" subtype="parallels"><!--N. P. Lichačev, Molivdovuly grečeskogo vostoka, Moskow 1991. add to bibliography as "Lichačev1991" and Ch. Chotzakoglou, Byzantinische Bleisiegel aus Ungarn, SBS 6, 1999, 59-70 as "Chotzakoglou1999"!-->
                <p>On followings seals, only the reverse is parallel to ours: (1) DO
                    BZS.1951.31.5.1214 (Fogg Collection, no. 1214) – <bibl><ptr
                            target="LaurentCorpus2"/>, no. <citedRange unit="entry"
                        >221</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="DOsealsOnline"/>, <citedRange
                            unit="entry"><ref
                                target="https://www.doaks.org/resources/seals/byzantine-seals/BZS.1951.31.5.1214/view"
                                >BZS.1951.31.5.1214</ref></citedRange></bibl>; (2) Saint Petersburg,
                    State Hermitage Museum, M-8047 – <bibl><ptr target="Lichačev1991"/>, p.
                            <citedRange unit="page">114</citedRange>, no. <citedRange unit="entry"
                            >8</citedRange>, table <citedRange unit="entry">LXIV</citedRange>, no.
                            <citedRange unit="entry">8</citedRange></bibl>; (3) Budapest, Hungarian
                    National Museum, no. 2A/1996 – <bibl><ptr target="Chotzakoglou1999"/>, p.
                            <citedRange unit="page">65</citedRange>, no. <citedRange unit="7"
                        /></bibl>. </p></div>
